Project Description
This project focused on designing and analyzing a new information system for National Booksellers Inc., a company that purchases books and CDs from vendors and resells them to retailers. The goal was to replace an outdated and inefficient system by building a scalable, user-friendly solution that could support increasing demand and improve overall performance .

I worked through the full systems analysis lifecycle, starting with defining the project scope and clearly separating functional requirements (such as order processing, inventory updates, and returns) from non-functional requirements (like system performance, user access control, and scalability across multiple locations) . From there, I developed Data Flow Diagrams (DFDs) to map how information moves through the system and Entity-Relationship Diagrams (ERDs) to structure the underlying data and relationships between customers, products, and vendors.

In addition to system modeling, I contributed to designing user interfaces for both customers and managers, including order entry forms, inventory dashboards, and reporting outputs. This helped translate technical system requirements into practical, user-facing features. Overall, the project strengthened my ability to think through complex systems end-to-end, balance high-level design with detailed requirements, and collaborate effectively in a team environment.
